2 Factor Analysis

2.1 Introduction

  • Factor analysis is used to estimate a model used to describe variance/covariance among observed, correlated variables by a set of lower number of unobserved variables called factors and weights.

Figure 2.1: Factor Analysis. In factor analysis model, we observed the variables values but not the Factor. Figure source: https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/stor-i-student-sites/hamish-thorburn/2020/01/24/factor-analysis-and-interpretability/

  • Uses: \[ \begin{cases} \text{Explain the variance/covariance of variables in a simple structure}\\ \text{Hypotheses testing}\\ \text{Dimension reduction} \end{cases} \]

With this project, we focus on the parametric method that rely on the normality of the data and will use EM algorithm to solve the model.

2.2 Factor analysis (with Gaussian assumption) model - Frame work

Assume that we observe \(n\) data points in \(d\) dimension \((x_1, ..., x_n)\) where \(x_i \in R^{d}, \forall i = \overline{1, n}\). The factor model postulate that \(x\) is linearly dependent upon a latent variable \(z \sim MVN(0, I_k)\), where \(k<d\) and random noise \(\epsilon \sim N(0, \Psi)\). To sum up, the frame work of factor analysis is

\[\begin{equation} \begin{cases} \text{latent variable: } z \sim N_k(0, I_k),\quad k<d \\ \text{random noise: } \epsilon \sim N_d(0, \Psi),\quad \Psi\in R^{d\times d}: \text{diagonal matrix} \\ \epsilon \text{ and } z \text{ are independent}\\ \text{observed variable } x = \mu + \Lambda z + \epsilon, \quad \mu\in R^d, \Lambda\in R^{d\times k} matrix \end{cases} \end{equation}\]

This factor model problem can be written as:

\[\begin{align} &z \sim N_k(0, I) \\ &x|z \sim N(\mu+\Lambda z, \Psi)\\ & \text{where } z \text{ is missing information}\\ & \text{parameters of interest: } \mu\in R^{d}, \Lambda \in R^{d\times k}, \Psi \in R^{d \times d} \end{align}\]

  • Example: Let’s consider an example that the latent variable \(z\) is in 1d and is map to \(x\) in 2d

\[\begin{align*} &n= 7, Z \sim N(0,1) \in R^1, x \in R^2\\ &x= \mu + \Lambda z + \epsilon = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} z + \epsilon \text{, where } \epsilon \sim N(0, \Psi), \Psi = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 2 \end{bmatrix} \end{align*}\]

Figure 2.2: An example of the latent variable z in 1d, it is mapped to x in 2d. The fig on the left-hand side demonstrates z, the points are mapped by a linear map to 2d (in the middle fig), and then add some noises (the right-hand side fig). The problem that Factor Analysis solves is: from the observed data x that we got from the fig. on the RHS, we find the linear map and also the variance of the noise. Source: the example is coded from the idea gotten from the lecture of Dr. Andrew Ng (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tw6cmL5STuY)

2.3 Solve the problem using EM

2.3.1 Complete data distribution function

We have the join complete data distribution is

\\tag{2.1}on}(#eq:joindist) \begin{bmatrix} z \\ x \end{bmatrix} \sim N(\mu_{zx}, \Sigma) \end{equation}\] where

\[\begin{equation} \begin{cases} \mu_{zx} = \begin{bmatrix} \vec{0} \\ \mu \end{bmatrix}\\ \Sigma = \begin{bmatrix} \Sigma_{11}& \Sigma_{12}\\ \Sigma_{21} & \Sigma_{22} \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} E[(z-Ez)(z-Ez)^T]& E[(z-Ez) (x-Ex)^T]\\ E[(x-Ex)(z-Ez)]& E[(x-Ex)(x-Ex)^T] \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} I & \Lambda^T\\ \Lambda & \Lambda \Lambda^T+ \Psi \end{bmatrix}\tag{2.2} \end{cases} \end{equation}\]

Proof:

  • We have the \(\mu_{zx}\) is computed by

\[\begin{equation*} \begin{cases} z \sim N(0,I) \Rightarrow \mu_z= E(z) = \vec{0}\\ x = \mu+\Lambda z+ \epsilon \Rightarrow E(x)=E(\mu+\Lambda z + \epsilon)=\mu \end{cases} \end{equation*}\]

  • Now, we will compute \(\Sigma_{ij}\), for \(i,j=\overline{1,n}\)

\[\begin{align*} \Sigma_{11} &= E(z) = \vec{0}\\ \Sigma_{12} &= E((z-Ez)(x-Ex)^T) = E(z(\mu+\Lambda z + \epsilon -\mu))\\ &= E(zz^T) \Lambda^T + E(z\epsilon^T) = \Lambda^T\\ \Sigma_{22}&= E((X-EX)(X-EX)^T)= E((\mu+\Lambda z+ \epsilon-\mu)(\mu+\Lambda z+ \epsilon-\mu)^T\\ &= E(\Lambda z z^T \Lambda^T + \Lambda z \epsilon^T+ \epsilon z^T \Lambda^T + \epsilon \epsilon^T)\\ &= E(\Lambda z z^T \Lambda^T+\epsilon \epsilon^T), \text{ since } E(z)=0\\ &= \Lambda E(zz^T)\Lambda^T + E(\epsilon \epsilon^T) = \Lambda I \Lambda^T + \Psi = \Lambda \Lambda^T + \Psi \end{align*}\]

2.3.2 Condition distribution of missing data over observed data and parameter

We have that \((z^{(s)}| x^{(s)}; \mu, \Lambda, \Psi) \sim N(\mu_{z^{(s)}| x^{(s)}}, \Sigma_{z^{(s)}| x^{(s)}})\), where

\[\begin{align} &\mu_{z^{(s)}| x^{(s)}} = \Lambda^T(\Lambda\Lambda^T + \Psi)^{-1} (x^{(s)}-\mu)\\ &\Sigma_{z^{(s)}| x^{(s)}} = I- \Lambda^T(\Lambda\Lambda^T + \Psi)^{-1}\Lambda \end{align}\]

Proof: The conditional distribution \((z^{(s)}| x^{(s)}; \mu, \Lambda, \Psi)\) is computed by substituting ((2.1) and ((2.2) to the conditional distribution of a Gaussian that is stated in the Appendix 4.1

2.3.3 M step

Here are the parameter estimators that maximize the \(Q\) function

\[\begin{align*} & \mu = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^n x^{(i)} } {n}\\ & \Lambda = \left(\sum_{i=1}^n (x^{(i)}-\mu) \mu_{z^{(i)}|x^{(i)}}^T\right) \left(\sum_{i=1}^n \mu_{z^{(i)}|x^{(i)}} \mu_{z^{(i)}|x^{(i)}}^T + \Sigma_{z^{(i)}|x^{(i)}}\right)^{-1}\\ & \phi = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n x^{(i)} x^{(i)^T} - x^{(i)} \mu_{z^{(i)}|x^{(i)}}^T \Lambda^T- \Lambda \mu_{z^{(i)}|x^{(i)}} x^{(i)^T} + \Lambda (\mu_{z^{(i)}|x^{(i)}} \mu_{z^{(i)}|x^{(i)}}^T + \Sigma_{z^{(i)}|x^{(i)}}) \Lambda^T\\ & \Psi_{ii} = \phi_{ii} \end{align*}\]

The proof for this result is quite lengthy but is stated clearly in (Ng 2000). A useful trick is that might be useful is

Let’s \(Q_i(z^{(i)})\) is the conditional distribution of \((z^{(s)}| x^{(s)}; \mu, \Lambda, \Psi)\), in the M step, we may need to compute \(\int_{z^{(i)}}Q_i(z^{(i)}) z^{(i)} dz^{(i)}\), in fact, the answer is simple since the integral equal \(E(z^{(i)})= \mu_{z^{(i)}|x^{(i)}}\)

2.4 Pseudo-code for EM for factor analysis

  1. Compute \(\mu = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^n x^{(i)} } {n}\)

  2. Set initial \(\Lambda\) and \(\Psi\).
    At each EM iteration, do

    1. Compute \[\begin{align*} &\mu_{z^{(s)}| x^{(s)}} = \Lambda^T(\Lambda\Lambda^T + \Psi)^{-1} (x^{(s)}-\mu)\\ &\Sigma_{z^{(s)}| x^{(s)}} = I- \Lambda^T(\Lambda\Lambda^T + \Psi)^{-1}\Lambda \end{align*}\]
    2. Compute \[\begin{align*} & \Lambda_{(new)} = \left(\sum_{i=1}^n (x^{(i)}-\mu) \mu_{z^{(i)}|x^{(i)}}^T\right) \left(\sum_{i=1}^n \mu_{z^{(i)}|x^{(i)}} \mu_{z^{(i)}|x^{(i)}}^T + \Sigma_{z^{(i)}|x^{(i)}}\right)^{-1}\\ & \phi_{(new)} = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n x^{(i)} x^{(i)^T} - x^{(i)} \mu_{z^{(i)}|x^{(i)}}^T \Lambda^T- \Lambda \mu_{z^{(i)}|x^{(i)}} x^{(i)^T} + \Lambda (\mu_{z^{(i)}|x^{(i)}} \mu_{z^{(i)}|x^{(i)}}^T + \Sigma_{z^{(i)}|x^{(i)}}) \Lambda^T\\ & \Psi_{ii(new)} = \phi_{ii} \end{align*}\]
    3. Update \(\Lambda\) and \(\Psi\)

  3. Stopping criteria for (2):

  • \(\Vert \Lambda\Vert< \epsilon\) and \(\Vert \Psi \Vert <\epsilon\)

3 Example of EM algorithm for Factor Analysis

Let’s see how the Factor analysis performs with the introduction example (2.2 with sample size \(n=500\).

With stopping criteria \(\Vert \theta\Vert < 0.0000001\), The EM converges at \(i=57\)

Parameter \(\mu\) \(\Lambda\) \(\Psi\)
True Values \(\begin{bmatrix}1\\1\end{bmatrix}\) \(\begin{bmatrix}2\\1\end{bmatrix}\) \(\begin{bmatrix}1&0\\0&2\end{bmatrix}\)
Initial \(\text{ }\) \(\begin{bmatrix}4\\1\end{bmatrix}\) \(\begin{bmatrix}3&0\\0&2\end{bmatrix}\)
Predicted \(\begin{bmatrix}0.95\\ 0.99\end{bmatrix}\) \(\begin{bmatrix}1.23\\0.86\end{bmatrix}\) \(\begin{bmatrix}4.41&0\\0&3.24\end{bmatrix}\)

With this example, the estimation for \(\Lambda\) is smaller than the actual value and the estimation for the co-variance matrix \(\Psi\) is bigger than the actual value.

4 Appendix

4.1 Marginals and conditionals of Gaussian

Suppose we have a vector-valued random variable

\[\begin{equation*} \boldsymbol{x} = \begin{bmatrix} x_1 \\ x_2 \end{bmatrix}\text{, where} x_1 \in R^r, x_2 \in R^s, \text{ and} x \in R^{r+s} \end{equation*}\]

Suppose \(x \sim N(\mu; \Sigma)\), where

\[\begin{align*} &\mu_{zx} = \begin{bmatrix} \mu_1 \\ \mu_2 \end{bmatrix}, \text{ where} \mu_1 \in R^r, \mu_2 \in R^s,\\ &\Sigma = \begin{bmatrix} \Sigma_{11}& \Sigma_{12}\\ \Sigma_{21} & \Sigma_{22} \end{bmatrix} \text{, where} \Sigma_{11} \in R^{r\times r}, \Sigma_{12} \in R^{r\times s}, \Sigma_{21}=\Sigma_{12}^T, \Sigma_{22}\in R^{s\times s} \end{align*}\]

  • The marginal distribution of \(x_1\) and \(x_2\): \[\begin{align} x_1 \sim N(\mu_1, \Sigma_{11})\\ x_2 \sim N(\mu_2, \Sigma_{22})\tag{4.1} \end{align}\]

Then we have

  • The Conditional distribution of \(x_1\) given \(x_2\) is \(x_1|x_2 \sim N(\mu_{1|2},\Sigma_{1|2})\), where

\[\begin{align} &\mu_{1|2} = \mu_1 + \Sigma_{12}\Sigma_{22}^{-1} (x_2 -\mu_2)\\ &\Sigma_{1|2} = \Sigma_{11}-\Sigma_{12}\Sigma_{22}^{-1}\Sigma_{21} \end{align}\]

5 Conclusion

Here is a note that I use to explore how the EM algorithm works for Factor Analysis. The R code, also, the introduction of the EM algorithm, and how it works for a Mixture of Gaussian distributions could be found [here]

In this project, we have explored the introduction of EM algorithm in the problem of Mixture of Gaussian with \(k=2\) and \(k>2\) distributions. Some examples with dimension \(d=1\) and \(d=2\) have been used to illustrate how the EM work. Through these examples, we have observed that the EM algorithm is sensitive to the initial values of parameters, the error in higher dimension might be higher than in lower dimension. Another problem need to be consider is how well the EM algorithm can perform in clustering problems with overlapping clusters. The paper (Yang, Lai, and Lin 2012) can be a good source to explore about how to improve the performance of the EM in this problem.

This project also have introduced about EM algorithm with Factor Analysis, we have observed one example when the estimation for the linear transformation matrix \(\Lambda\) is smaller than the actual value and the estimation for the co-variance matrix \(\Psi\) is bigger than the actual value. The article (Zhao, Yu, and Jiang 2008) and Chapter 5 of the book (McLachlan and Krishnan 2007) could be used to explore more about this problem.
